{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e5ed93c3-1952-4349-b8a7-cb12e0df9820","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the container:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace** (e.g., 30 seconds):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\n# From your local machine:\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView** (Windows), or convert to **speedscope** format for browser viewing:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n# Then open at https://speedscope.app\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or ephemeral debug container: `kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 --target=<container>`\n- For production, prefer `--duration` or `Ctrl+C` to keep trace sizes manageable.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a good quick first step to confirm CPU is actually in managed code before tracing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"679a27b3-3ec4-4545-92ef-a34da478330e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics/troubleshooting question that doesn't require code changes or file exploration. I can answer from knowledge.","outputTokens":457,"requestId":"D82D:112B3A:30D5DED:35B6F90:69FBEB38"},"id":"d9b1d768-3128-44ff-9544-7b7d18079d58","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:30:44.444Z","parentId":"5095c4cf-8d83-4caa-a2e0-904e281843e9"}
